Per [the documentation](https://supabase.com/docs/guides/realtime/broadcast#send-messages) for broadcasting messages, a channel must first be subscribed to before it can call the `send` method. 

However, `channel.subscribe` does not return a promise and only executes its callback. This means that if you're calling this example from the documentation...
```javascript
const channel = supabase.channel('test')

channel.subscribe((status) => {
  if (status === 'SUBSCRIBED') {
    channel.send({
      type: 'broadcast',
      event: 'supa',
      payload: { org: 'supabase' },
    })
  }
})
```

...in a short-lived context like an AWS Lambda function, the process may die before the callback is executed. In this particular case, it would be more natural to say something like:

```javascript
const channel = supabase.channel('test')

await channel.subscribed();

channel.send({
  type: 'broadcast',
  event: 'supa',
  payload: { org: 'supabase' },
})
```

Does that make sense? Am I overlooking existing functionality?

Of course, one option developers have is to write their own promise. I was able to write the following code to accomplish the same task:

```javascript
const channel = supabase.channel("test");

const channelSubscribed = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  channel.subscribe((status) => {
    if (status === 'SUBSCRIBED') {
      resolve(channel);
    } else {
       reject("Could not subscribe to channel");
    }
  })
});

await channelSubscribed.then((channel) => {
  channel.send({
    type: 'broadcast',
    event: 'supa',
    payload: { org: 'supabase' },
  })
})
```

