# Improve documentation

## Link 

https://supabase.com/docs/guides/getting-started/tutorials/with-sveltekit

## Describe the problem

```js
  async function signOut() {
    try {
      loading = true
      let { error } = await supabase.auth.signOut()
      if (error) throw error
    } catch (error) {
      if (error instanceof Error) {
        alert(error.message)
      }
    } finally {
      loading = false
    }
  }
```

The error is handled twice: `if (error) ` and `catch (error)`. It is not clear if `await signOut()` can throw even without the `if`.

## Describe the improvement

If the `error` is not an `Error` but an object with metadata, the above should look like this:

```js
  async function signOut() {
    loading = true
    const { errorDetails: error } = await supabase.auth.signOut()
    if (errorDetails) {
        // handle error here, assuming the handler does not throw
    }
    loading = false
  }
```

If the `error` is an instance of `Error`, then it should look like this:

```js
const throwable = async (promise) => {
    const result = await promise;
    if (result?.error) {
        throw result.error;
    }
    return result?.data ?? result;
};

  async function signOut() {
    loading = true
    try {
        await throwable(supabase.auth.signOut())
    } catch (error) {
      if (error instanceof Error) {
        alert(error.message)
      }
    } finally {
      loading = false
    }
  }
```

If the original is still desired, it should be documented whether `signOut()` (or any other async function) throws or not.

